ass=m><span class=title>   Re: What makes a good puller?</span><hr size=1> One thing that helps keep adds down is keeping track of the spawns you are pulling. If you're in a dungeon, get to know where all the spawn points are and where wanderers go, and get used to timing the first couple of spawns. After  that you'll know that in say 30 seconds the next 1 will spawn, then the next etc - gives you the advantage of knowing what should be around before you even get there.<br>
<br>
Also be aware of what you can single pull and what you cant. Generally if 2 mobs are standing within aggro range of each other and you only want one, pull the higher level mob first. Dependant on level you can sometimes or always pull singles or at least leave the lower level mobs in a room behind for later. Level plays a very important part in  how many mobs chain aggro, at 56 in sebilis you will agrro pretty much everything (not always a bad thing if your group kills fast), at 60 most rooms on the top level can be single/double pulled.<br>
<br>
If you are pulling past another group of people, make sure you do some damage to the mob first (so long as it doesnt summon!). This will make it ignore the other peeps and follow you. Generally in a dungeon like seb I try to do 300 or so damage if I have to pull past others.<br>
<br>
Shame you dont play a hobbit :P One of our advantages is we can sneak pull, great for controlling pulls when your group is subpar.<br>
<br>
Ooh just thought of another thing, pulling casters can be very annoying, as they tend to sit back and nuke you rather than follow back to camp immediately. The trick I use is to hide behind a wall or in an alcove so I am out of  Line of Sight. It has to run to you then =)<br>
<br>
Its definitely worth learning how to pull well as you'll be expected to do it a lot in exp dungeons - it also gives you a nice headstart on aggro. Dont be afraid to ask more experienced people in your group for any specific advice on pulling certain camps, and just remember that everyone gets bad pulls sometimes, its not always your fault.<br>
