<br>
-situational awareness; know what's going on in your group, in your area, etc.  How is mana, is a train coming, has the cleric fallen asleep AGAIN, etc.<br>
<br>
-very good sense of direction (don't get lost pulling thru mazes or over hills), good maps, and a stopwatch or timer.  Keep track of the pulls, where they came from and when they died, to avoid ugly respawn trains.  Knowing how to run backwards to your camp is sometimes quite useful too...<br>
<br>
-understanding how the pathing works in that particular zone; below a certain distance, a mob paths directly to you; beyond that it tries to use the brain-dead pathing algorithms that some designer put into the zone as an afterthought.  Know when to walk a mob into camp, and when to run one in.<br>
<br>
-UNDERSTAND HOW AGGRO REALLY WORKS.  It's very straight forward and logical, but it's truely AMAZING how many &quot;good&quot; pullers have no real clue how and why it does what it does.  This includes understanding level distances, line of sight, range and elevation effects, effects of &quot;retained&quot; aggro, etc. etc. etc.<br>
<br>
-self sacrifice; mark of a good puller is knowing when to stop and die, and where to leave his/her corpse, to avoid training the group (or others) AND make the CR of said corpse easy.  Knowing when to call for a CoH is a good skill too. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
-lots and lots of situational resist and pulling gear.  For pulling in a place like PoG for instance, PILES of MR, CR, FR and DR stuff is required (everything there either roots, fire nukes, or cold/disease dots).  Regen helps a ton, as do clicky dispel items, self-cast sow and lev, etc.<br>
<br>
-using the right pulling technique for the right situation.  Sometimes using a bow is fine, other times a clicky debuff/dispel is appropriate, and other times /con pulling-prox aggro is best.<br>
<br>
-experience; work on it and pay attention to what works well AND what doesn't work at all, learning/remembering to repeat the former and avoid the latter on a consistent basis. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
