<br>
I'll agree that warriors have to understand pulling better than monks because they don't have the &quot;get out of jail free card&quot; of FD.  If you pull too much for your group to handle as a warrior your only choices are to train the zone or die.  Pulling is different in every zone, and it's always trial and error for the first few pulls.  Don't be scared to experiment, and you group should be understanding of a few bad pulls if you've never been there before.  You might have to die a time or two, or pull a couple trains, but if you experiment a little, learn the quirks in pathing, try different things, etc. you will get to where you can pull anywhere very well.<br>
<br>
Sometimes an arrow is the best way to do it.  Sometimes it's inching up to a mob, sometimes it's aggroing through walls, or tagging from the right angle so they path to you and don't decide it's faster to go through half the dungeon and bring half of their friends, or using line of sight.  Sometimes it's knowing what the highest level mob in the group is and tagging him first.  Sometimes it's just having a certain level.  I know 54 was the magic level to pull in KC, and 58 was the one for kobolds in Velks.<br>
<br>
My favorite area of all time to pull was the caedosaur bridge in chardok.  Talk about a nail-biter hehe, it was a total rush to pull those things for an exp group, and I was truely disappointed when they took em out.<br>
<br>
If you don't pull as a warrior, you're missing out on one of the best parts of the class IMO, and once you get used to pulling, sitting in the group and hitting taunt, bash, disarm and melee attack is just painfully boring. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6629>Brutul Vilesilencer</a><br>

